As far as I know, the reason that the letter <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> H</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is there in the first place is merely because ‚µ is pronounced more like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> shi</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> si</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uamanohashidate.showPublicProfile?language=EN>amanohashidate</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/17/02 3:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=860.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Simple question, Doushite?</span><hr size=1> Howdy,<br>
<br>
The process of converting Japanese sounds into English Letters is called Romanization. There are several versions floating around with minor differences. The most common one is the Modified Hepburn, which tries to spell the Japanese sounds as you might hear them. The Japanese ministry of education uses an old fashioned romanization which modifies the English spelling to get a more standardized chart. Both romanizations are pronounced exactly the same.<br>
<br>
Thus the Hepburn has the &quot;s&quot; row like:<br>
<br>
sa shi su se so<br>
<br>
While the Ministry verision goes like:<br>
<br>
sa si su se so<br>
<br>
Likewise, the &quot;t&quot; row in Hepburn:<br>
<br>
ta chi tsu te to<br>
<br>
In Ministry:<br>
<br>
ta ti tu te to<br>
<br>
If you follow the Hepburn to get your pronunciation cues, you'll be doing fine.<br>
<br>
Best,<br>
